    <!-- Talk details -->
    <section>
        <h3>Talk Title</h3>
        <p><strong>Engineering Trust in Surgical AI: Benchmarking Robustness and Homologation in Higher-Risk Domains</strong></p>

        <h3>Abstract</h3>
        <p>
            Surgery has always advanced through the careful adoption of new technologies—anesthesia, antisepsis, imaging,
            and minimally invasive techniques—integrated through pragmatic evaluation, comparison, and standard setting.
            Artificial intelligence represents the next inevitable inflection point in this continuum.
        </p>
        <p>
            This lecture presents a domain-level perspective on how AI is being introduced into surgery, not as a purely
            technical problem, but as a systems challenge that requires benchmarking, transparency, and shared definitions
            of success. Drawing on work led within the surgical community, including consensus standards and the SAGES
            Critical View of Safety Challenge, the talk describes how clinicians and engineers have collaborated to design
            datasets, metrics, and competitions that allow models to be compared, stress-tested, and iteratively improved
            in clinically meaningful ways.
        </p>
        <p>
            Rather than focusing on algorithmic novelty, the lecture emphasizes how high-stakes fields operationalize AI:
            how benchmarks are constructed, how failure modes are exposed, how trust is earned, and how performance
            standards evolve toward real-world use. The goal is to illustrate how principles familiar from other engineering
            domains—such as benchmarking and homologation—can emerge organically within medicine and generalize to other
            safety-critical applications of AI.
        </p>

    

